pullRequest.body:
define the field structure on the Surreal numbers

---

- [x] depends on: #14463
- [x] depends on: #14600 
- [x] depends on: #14517 

In this PR, we prove that the inverse defined in `SetTheory/Game/Basic` is indeed a multiplicative inverse. The bulk of the proof is in the new file `SetTheory/Surreal/Division`. Right now, the proof is a bit repetitive as there are usually many similar cases which differ only in small places like Left vs Right. Suggestions for how to improve the proof are welcome.

Looking pretty good structurally, but I haven't read the proofs at all. 

Would someone from amongst @timotree3, @FR-vdash-bot, @vihdzp, who have been thinking about games and surreals recently, be able to give a review? 

Particularly useful would be checking that the proofs look reasonable, and perhaps suggesting names for lemmas. (I'm a little uncomfortable with `eq1` etc and `onag` in names, but perhaps just making these private is good enough, or even the fact that they are already well namespaced.)

I must admit that I've never actually read ONAG past the first few pages. My interest of games in Lean was motivated foremost by the fact their API is very similar to that of ordinals (in fact, ordinals are just games when you remove right options!), which is a topic I'm much more familiar in. That said, I really don't want this PR to rot over the following months. I'll try reading up to surreal division throughout the next week or so, and if no one else has stepped in by then, I'll give a proper PR review.
I opened #15779 which should help golf down the results on `normalization` a bit.
Initial remarks on `normalize`.
I haven't really delved into the main proof just yet. I think there's a lot that can be improved in readability beforehand.
This is a non-terminal simp, and should be squeezed to a `simp only`
Indeed!
I've forgotten my ONAG: if this is useful beyond setting up the field structure, perhaps this could preemptively be moved to its own file? Otherwise fine as is.
I don't see this normalization used in ONAG beyond setting up the field structure.
Can we use `Option xl` instead?
My PR #15779 does just that.

```suggestion
lemma one_def : 1 = mk 1 numeric_one := rfl
```

```suggestion
We essentially follow the proof in ONAG [Conway2001], chapter 1, theorem 10, with a few minor
```

```suggestion
lemma right_pos_of_pos (j) : 0 < x.moveRight j :=
  x_pos.trans (x_num.lt_moveRight j)
```
This seems too easy for a lemma. If we really wanted it, we could generalize `0` by any other pre-game, or even change `0 < x` to `0 ≤ x`, but then that's too contrived for a one-liner.

```suggestion
lemma Numeric.normalization : (normalization x).Numeric := by
```
This might require moving some namespaces around.

```suggestion
  rcases x with ⟨xl, xr, xL, xR⟩
  rw [normalization]
  apply insertLeft_numeric _ numeric_zero _
  · rw [numeric_def] at x_num ⊢
    simp only [leftMoves_mk, rightMoves_mk, moveLeft_mk, moveRight_mk, Subtype.forall] at x_num ⊢
    simp only [x_num, implies_true, and_self]
  · rw [PGame.zero_le]
    simpa only [rightMoves_mk, moveRight_mk] using PGame.zero_le.1 <| x_pos.le
```

```suggestion
def normalization : PGame → PGame
  | ⟨_, r, L, R⟩ => insertLeft ⟨{i // 0 < L i}, r, fun i => L i, R⟩ 0
```

I think it might be useful to separate out `⟨{i // 0 < L i}, r, fun i => L i, R⟩` into another auxiliary definition, maybe `normalization'`. That way you can separate the proofs of `normalization'` and `normalization` being numbers, and equivalent to the numbers they normalize. Somewhere along those lines, you'd use
```
theorem insertLeft_congr_left {x y z : PGame} (h : x ≈ y) : insertLeft x z ≈ insertLeft y z := by
  sorry
```
which is currently missing from the library.

Note that `Numeric.normalization'` does not require `0 < x`.

Actually, my `normalization'` isn't always equivalent to the original game, consider {0 | }. For that reason, `insertLeft_congr_left` won't always work. So this might not have been such a good suggestion.

It's not good practice to have conditions on variables. You might then miss cases when they're not strictly necessary. For instance, `Numeric.normalization` only requires `0 ≤ x` (though I guess it does make sense to instead require `0 < x`).

```suggestion
lemma eq_normalization_of_pos:
    mk x x_num = mk (normalization x) (num_of_normalization_num x_num x_pos) := by
  rw [mk_eq_mk]
   -- we show: x ≈ x.insertLeft 0 ≈ normalization x
  apply trans <| symm <| insertLeft_equiv_of_lf x_pos.lf
  rw [equiv_def]
  rcases x with ⟨xl, xr, xL, xR⟩
  simp only [normalization, insertLeft]
  constructor <;> (
    rw [le_def]
    simp only [leftMoves_mk, moveLeft_mk, Sum.exists, Sum.elim_inl, Subtype.exists,
      Sum.elim_inr, exists_const, Sum.forall, le_refl, or_true, IsEmpty.exists_iff,
      or_false, implies_true, and_true, moveRight_mk]
  ) <;>
  constructor <;>
  intro i
  · left
    cases' le_or_gf (xL i) 0 with h h
    · right; exact h
    · left; use i, h.lt numeric_zero (x_num.moveLeft _)
  · right; use i
  · left; left; use i
  · right; use i
```
It might be possible to golf this further, `le_def` is usually strictly worse than `le_iff_forall_lf` or `le_iff_forall_lt`.

```suggestion
  induction i <;> rw [invVal]
  · exact numeric_zero
  all_goals
    case _ i j ih =>
      apply Numeric.mul
      · apply numeric_one.add <| (Numeric.sub _ h5).mul ih
        · first | exact h5.2.1 i | exact h5.2.2 i
      · first | exact h4 i | exact h3 i i.2
```

```suggestion
lemma numeric_inv' (ih_xl : ∀ i, 0 < x.moveLeft i → (x.moveLeft i).inv'.Numeric)
```
This name is a bit too close to that of `Numeric.inv'`, so maybe something like `numeric_inv'_of_numeric_options` is better.
Is it really worth it having these separate left and right statements if they can be so easily gotten out of `inv'_numeric`?

```suggestion
    (i'' : InvTy {i // 0 < L i} r b) : Surreal × Surreal × Surreal :=
```
Can you specify what these variables represent in the docstring?

This, if perhaps not in this preliminary form, seems like a potentially useful equality later down the line. So I think it makes sense to try and come up with a better name. Maybe `one_neg_div_option`?
This is a really unwieldy type signature. Can you put that in a separate def with a docstring explaining what's going on?

```suggestion
    | _ => 1 - x * y'' = (1 - x * y') * (x' - x) * x'_inv := by
```
This could be turned into a def too.

If I understand correctly, what this inductive proof does is
a) take care of all numericity hypotheses first
b) cast your values into elements of `Surreal*`
c) delegate all the actual calculations to `field_simp; ring`
Can you add a few short comments in the proof explaining this?

Maybe something like this?
```suggestion
    (hnum_L : ∀ i, 0 < L i → (L i).inv'.Numeric)
    (hnum_R : ∀ j, (R j).inv'.Numeric) (hnum : (PGame.mk l r L R).Numeric) {b : Bool}
```
Really, anything more descriptive would be nice. Alternatively, you could turn these hypothesis into `def`s like in the surreal multiplication proof.
Most of the same comments on the previous proof apply here. Maybe this could be named `one_between_mul_options`?
`mul_option_eq_one_add_mul`?
`mul_option_lt_one`?
`one_lt_mul_option`?
`numeric_inv'_and_inv_surreal`? Honestly it's probably fine to just name this one `main`.

```suggestion
lemma Numeric.inv' : (x.inv').Numeric := (onag_1_10 x_num x_pos).1
```

```suggestion
lemma mul_inv'_self : x * x.inv' ≈ 1 := (onag_1_10 x_num x_pos).2
```

```suggestion
protected lemma mul_inv_self (hx : ¬ x ≈ 0) : x * x⁻¹ ≈ 1 := by
```
With `protected`, this doesn't work - then Lean cannot find this `mul_inv_self` when it is used later in this file. I removed the `protected` and it works.

The `protected` keyword makes it so that you have to specify the namespace explicitly, i.e. `Surreal.mul_inv_self`. That way, the name of this lemma can correspond to the analogous [`mul_inv_self`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Group/Defs.html#mul_inv_self) in the root namespace without clashing with it.

According to [this](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/74ed7693458847faae657f3489f6d1d228607280/Mathlib/Algebra/Group/Defs.lean#L1073) `mul_inv_self` is deprecated in favor of `mul_inv_cancel` so perhaps I should use `mul_inv_cancel` here also ?
I changed `mul_inv_self` to `mul_inv_cancel`, added `protected` keyword, and also renamed `mul_inv'_self` to `mul_inv'_cancel`.
Is it simpler to use `lt_or_equiv_or_gt`?
